			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Last night, my guild tried to do the HO's without using teamspeak. I'm a n00b at macros so I just made a simple macro that said "HO Starting in 5 seconds". This gave everyone a chance to finish the spell they were casting or get that heal out before I started the HO. 
<br />

<br />
In our group we had a warrior, enchanter, cleric, druid, bard and a sorcerer. I'm the bard  <img src="images/smiles/icon_biggrin.gif" alt="Very Happy" border="0" /> We were working on the 4 icon HO's to get more info about them. We discussed what HO we were going for. Started the fight and let the enchanter crowd control. He signaled when he was done and we could start HO's. I would use my macro and 5 seconds later I would hit Lucky Break. It worked very well. It just takes some group coordination to get it done.
<br />

<br />
I have pretty much stopped mashing my attacks. I use a lot of attacks at the beginning of the fight while the enchanter mezzes. Then I use a flurry of them whenever the HO wheel is up. Other then that, I'm using auto attack to deal out the damage. It seems to be rather effective and while there isn't much downtime in the game, we had almost none the whole night.
<br />

<br />
As a side note, we got out Past's Awakening last night (before we got it to come up but couldn't complete). Our group level was about 15. It hit the mob we were fighting for 442 points of damage. Not to mention Ancient Demise which hit everything in the encounter for about 130 each. I believe both of these were orange con encounters.
<br />

<br />
So yeah, assigning a HO starter seems to work well. And if you have two of the same class in your group. Assign one to starter chains and the other to the HO wheel. Not only will it be simpler, but you'll do more damage because more people were involved in the HO.
<br />

<br />
Thanks for the feedback, I hope it makes more sense to you now.
<br />
Kresken</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
